  "prompt": "An atom has electrons, protons and neutrons. But what's in the electrons, protons or neutrons?",
  "response": "At the fundamental level, electrons, protons, and neutrons are considered elementary particles with different compositions:\n\n1. Electrons:\n- Considered a fundamental (elementary) particle\n- Cannot be broken down into smaller components\n- A fundamental particle of the lepton family\n- Has a negative electric charge\n\n2. Protons:\n- Composed of quarks (specifically 2 up quarks and 1 down quark)\n- These quarks are held together by gluons\n- Part of the hadron family\n\n3. Neutrons:\n- Also composed of quarks (1 up quark and 2 down quarks)\n- Like protons, they are held together by gluons\n- Also part of the hadron family\n\nSo while electrons are truly elementary particles, protons and neutrons are composite particles made up of quarks. The quarks themselves are held together by the strong nuclear force mediated by gluons.\n\nIn the Standard Model of particle physics, these are the most fundamental known components of atoms, though ongoing research continues to explore even deeper levels of particle structure.",
